<i>Look at me</i>

00:01.468 --> 00:04.836
<i>I'm as helpless</i>
<i>as a kitten</i>

00:04.905 --> 00:06.532
<i>Up a tree</i>

00:09.477 --> 00:13.811
Didn't you know your partner
is the most famous policeman
in the whole of Europe?

00:14.215 --> 00:15.239
Mmm.

00:15.316 --> 00:17.284
You fell for that
handsome, charming bit.

00:17.351 --> 00:19.148
"Have this little
water chestnut,
Jean Claude."

00:19.220 --> 00:20.983
I think you're
actually jealous.

00:21.055 --> 00:22.454
You're sure
you don't want
to change your mind?

00:22.523 --> 00:25.185
I'm just gonna
stay in the box
till everybody leaves,

00:25.259 --> 00:27.193
then I'll find out
what's going on.

00:27.962 --> 00:29.429
<i>Attention!</i> Duck!

04:00.993 --> 04:03.393
<i>"Ice water</i>
<i>surged through his veins</i>

04:03.462 --> 04:07.990
"as the Inspector
looked down the barrel
of a 9 millimeter automatic

04:08.067 --> 04:10.297
"held by the same man
who had so cavalierly

04:10.369 --> 04:12.769
"caused the death
of his pretty wife."

04:12.838 --> 04:15.705
Oh, no!
Doesn't he know
about the trapdoor?

04:15.775 --> 04:17.800
Of course, he does.
He saw it in the last page.

04:17.877 --> 04:19.469
Then why is he
standing there?

04:19.545 --> 04:21.843
Carol, if you'd listen,
please.

04:21.914 --> 04:23.472
Okay, all right.

04:23.716 --> 04:26.583
It's only the first
chapter, anyway.
The hero can't die.

04:26.652 --> 04:28.449
Right.
May I continue?

04:29.422 --> 04:31.686
"The sneering satyr
of a man..."

04:35.261 --> 04:38.697
"The sneering
satyr of a man
raised the gun,

04:38.764 --> 04:40.026
"about to squeeze
the trigger,

04:40.099 --> 04:42.533
"when suddenly a shout
was heard from above."

04:42.601 --> 04:43.727
Magnum!

04:45.037 --> 04:47.403
I demand
an explanation.

04:47.840 --> 04:50.468
Oh, we were just getting to
the explanation, Jonathan.

04:50.543 --> 04:53.512
Right.
About why you broke
into the study safe

04:53.579 --> 04:57.777
and absconded with the galleys
of Mr. Masters' new novel,
<i>Die And Die Again.</i> Why?

04:58.284 --> 05:00.616
Why? Why?

05:01.754 --> 05:02.846
Because...

05:02.922 --> 05:04.787
I made him do it.

05:04.857 --> 05:07.121
I just...
I couldn't wait
for the book to come out.

05:07.193 --> 05:09.388
And then to read it
in the sea air,
in the sand,

05:09.462 --> 05:11.623
while consuming
alcoholic beverages.

05:11.697 --> 05:14.757
Isn't that the way
a Robin Masters novel
is supposed to be read?

05:14.834 --> 05:15.892
Not this one.

05:15.968 --> 05:19.665
This particular book is not
to be read by anyone until
publication, including myself.

05:19.739 --> 05:21.900
Mr. Masters left
strict instructions

05:21.974 --> 05:24.602
that it is to be locked away
until he can get here
next week

05:24.677 --> 05:26.804
to make
the final revisions.

05:27.012 --> 05:30.072
And you, you should be
particularly ashamed
of yourself.

05:30.950 --> 05:34.010
Right.
I'm sorry, Jonathan.

05:34.754 --> 05:37.951
I'm just a paperback junkie.
I don't know, sometimes it...

05:38.023 --> 05:41.151
I don't know what to do.
I just can't control myself.

05:43.796 --> 05:45.525
I guess I'll go home now.

05:47.266 --> 05:50.463
By the by, there's a client
waiting for you in my study.

05:50.603 --> 05:52.195
Your study?

05:53.272 --> 05:54.569
Quite.

05:54.673 --> 05:56.732
A friend
of Mr. Masters.

05:56.809 --> 05:59.505
Although a sadly
misguided one,
apparently.

05:59.612 --> 06:02.206
However, you should know
that your potential client,

06:02.281 --> 06:05.250
and I say potential
because I'm sure that once
he's spoken to you

06:05.317 --> 06:07.308
the relationship
will proceed no further,

06:07.386 --> 06:10.913
is a man of extremely
delicate sensibilities and...

06:23.869 --> 06:26.269
Perhaps just one
small chapter.

06:31.777 --> 06:33.210
Unthinkable.

06:33.579 --> 06:35.171
...but not unpleasant.

06:40.286 --> 06:44.279
After all,
a job such as mine
has its advantage.

06:44.890 --> 06:46.721
Am I not
in paradise?

06:46.892 --> 06:49.884
You are in my study,
<i>Monsieur</i> Chabrol.

06:50.863 --> 06:52.125
<i>Bien sûr.</i>

06:52.665 --> 06:55.896
Uh...
Robin Masters' study?

06:58.537 --> 06:59.629
Quite.

07:00.039 --> 07:04.635
However, Robin Masters
is neither known
for his sensitive prose

07:04.710 --> 07:06.268
nor his sensitive palate.

07:06.812 --> 07:10.680
No doubt the excellent
taste of liqueur

07:10.749 --> 07:12.774
is yours,
<i>Monsieur</i> Higgins.

07:15.721 --> 07:17.450
But, as I was saying,

07:17.523 --> 07:21.152
I, Francois Chabrol,
am a heir hunter.

07:21.227 --> 07:25.425
And Robin Masters suggested
that I, how do you say,
look you over,

07:25.498 --> 07:28.365
when I come to Hawaii.
You mean, "Look me up"?

07:28.734 --> 07:30.599
I just have.
Ah.

07:31.237 --> 07:33.137
To find
a missing duke.

07:33.405 --> 07:36.897
I dare say what you're asking
may be somewhat out
of Magnum's line.

07:37.076 --> 07:38.543
I don't think so.

07:38.611 --> 07:41.842
Many times,
as Robin and I
sipped cognac,

07:41.914 --> 07:44.348
on the veranda
of his villa,

07:44.617 --> 07:47.415
surveying the sights
of the Cote d'Azur,

07:47.720 --> 07:50.655
he would tell me all about
the great exploits

07:51.423 --> 07:54.119
of Thomas Magnum,
private investigator.

07:54.760 --> 07:57.058
Naturally, I was
quite impressed.

07:58.097 --> 08:00.224
Thank you.
You are most welcome.

08:00.733 --> 08:05.432
You see, I was struck by the
similarities between what you
do and what I do.

08:05.905 --> 08:09.306
But with me,
there is almost always
a happy ending.

08:09.575 --> 08:12.271
I travel the world looking
for the black sheep.

08:12.444 --> 08:15.777
The runaways,
the illegitimate children.

08:17.049 --> 08:19.574
You would be
surprised to realize

08:19.652 --> 08:22.382
just how many
heirs there are,

08:22.454 --> 08:25.446
how do you say,
on the lamp.

08:25.925 --> 08:27.085
Lam.

08:27.426 --> 08:28.757
Of course.

08:30.262 --> 08:34.130
But for there to be
a happy ending this time,

08:34.633 --> 08:35.998
I need your help.

08:38.169 --> 08:39.296
Well,

08:39.371 --> 08:42.602
sure, I could
show you around a little bit,
I guess.

08:43.708 --> 08:47.372
But, I must tell you,
Francois, that, uh,

08:48.314 --> 08:51.875
I don't have
a whole lot of contacts
among runaway royalty.

08:52.117 --> 08:56.076
Of course,
I will split my commission
from the estate with you.

08:56.255 --> 08:59.315
How do you say, 50-50?

09:00.125 --> 09:02.252
In this particular instance,

09:02.328 --> 09:05.559
the illegitimate
scion of a duke,

09:06.332 --> 09:11.167
it could perhaps
come up to a few
hundred thousand dollars.

09:13.706 --> 09:16.732
On the other hand,
I'm sure Magnum will be
quite willing to assist.

09:16.809 --> 09:19.607
Of course.
As a favor
to Mr. Masters.

09:22.581 --> 09:26.073
As a favor to Mr. Masters?
<i>Magnifique.</i>

09:29.254 --> 09:31.688
Do you have any leads?

09:32.658 --> 09:34.182
But of course.

09:35.294 --> 09:37.387
<i>Admittedly,</i>
<i>it was a strange clue.</i>

09:37.463 --> 09:40.864
<i>I mean, whoever heard</i>
<i>of looking for a missing duke</i>
<i>on the waterfront?</i>

09:40.933 --> 09:44.596
<i>Especially one who apparently</i>
<i>worked at a Japanese</i>
<i>import-export house</i>

09:44.670 --> 09:47.002
<i>and had a nickname</i>
<i>of The Pearl.</i>

09:47.473 --> 09:49.668
<i>At any rate,</i>
<i>one thing for sure</i>

09:49.742 --> 09:53.269
<i>is you can't just go to</i>
<i>the personnel departments</i>
<i>of these waterfront places,</i>

09:53.345 --> 09:55.245
<i>because there usually</i>
<i>aren't any.</i>

09:55.314 --> 09:58.283
<i>The kind of guys who work</i>
<i>on the docks usually don't</i>
<i>want anybody knowing</i>

09:58.350 --> 09:59.840
<i>who or where they are.</i>

09:59.918 --> 10:01.818
<i>And usually,</i>
<i>with good reason.</i>

10:01.920 --> 10:05.117
<i>So, you have to do</i>
<i>the next best thing,</i>

10:05.190 --> 10:07.784
<i>which is to go into the bars</i>
<i>where these guys hang out,</i>

10:07.860 --> 10:12.092
<i>make friends with them,</i>
<i>do what they do</i>
<i>and, like Francois said,</i>

10:12.197 --> 10:15.098
<i>there's always</i>
<i>a happy ending. Right?</i>

10:15.701 --> 10:19.000
Sing Sing.
Like the famous prison?

10:19.071 --> 10:21.437
Not exactly.
Like what?

10:21.840 --> 10:25.469
Well, like Edith Piaf,
Charles Aznavour,
Maurice Chevalier.

10:25.544 --> 10:28.035
Ah, Elvis Presley,
"the King."
Yeah, you got it.

10:29.381 --> 10:31.508
<i>I get so Ionely</i>

10:31.984 --> 10:36.785
<i>I get so Ionely</i>
<i>I could die</i>

10:46.732 --> 10:48.700
Okay. H-12.

10:48.834 --> 10:50.768
Do you guys
want a booth?
Yes, please.

10:50.836 --> 10:52.895
Okay.
I'll be right back.

10:55.307 --> 10:59.038
<i>Good-bye Joe, he gotta go,</i>
<i>me oh my oh</i>

10:59.812 --> 11:03.646
<i>He gotta go pole the pirogue</i>
<i>down the bayou</i>

11:04.616 --> 11:08.211
<i>My Yvonne the sweetest one,</i>
<i>me oh my oh</i>

11:09.655 --> 11:11.418
<i>Son of a gun...</i>

11:11.490 --> 11:12.957
I'll be right back.

11:16.061 --> 11:20.896
This is very interesting.
But how does this help me
find the Duke Du Rochefort?

11:20.966 --> 11:24.800
You mean, The Pearl?
<i>Oui,</i> The Pearl.

11:24.870 --> 11:27.703
Well, if he works down here,
pretty soon we're gonna
run into somebody

11:27.773 --> 11:29.297
who knows him,
or knows of him.

11:29.374 --> 11:30.432
I see.

11:30.509 --> 11:34.138
So, all we gotta do
is settle back,
have a couple of cold ones,

11:34.213 --> 11:36.613
get with the flow,
and pretty soon

11:36.682 --> 11:39.173
we'll be talking to somebody
who can probably help us out.

11:39.251 --> 11:41.310
<i>C'est bon.</i>
<i>Oui.</i>

11:42.888 --> 11:45.254
Hi.
Cognac.

11:45.324 --> 11:47.622
A couple of longnecks,
please.

11:48.794 --> 11:50.591
What's your pleasure,
gentlemen?

11:50.662 --> 11:52.596
Oh, no, that's okay.
We're not here to sing.

11:52.664 --> 11:54.529
We're just going to have
a couple of beers.

11:54.600 --> 11:58.434
Sorry, but this table
is reserved for singers...

11:58.504 --> 12:01.371
Yeah, but...
But that's the way
we stay in business.

12:01.974 --> 12:05.341
If you want beers,
go to the regular bar.

